"Menon S., Soberón J., Li X., Peterson A.T.","Preliminary global assessment of terrestrial biodiversity consequences of sea-level rise mediated by climate change",2010,"Biodiversity and Conservation","19","6",,"1599","1609",,,10.1007/s10531-010-9790-4,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77952240929&partnerID=40&md5=471d89e18a6497d22866e89b36f64e81","Department of Biology, Grand Valley State University, Allendale, MI 49401-9403, United States; Natural History Museum and Biodiversity Research Center, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Department of Geography, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States","Menon, S., Department of Biology, Grand Valley State University, Allendale, MI 49401-9403, United States; Soberón, J., Natural History Museum and Biodiversity Research Center, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Li, X., Department of Geography, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Peterson, A.T., Natural History Museum and Biodiversity Research Center, The University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States","Considerable attention has focused on the climatic effects of global climate change on biodiversity, but few analyses and no broad assessments have evaluated effects of sea-level rise on biodiversity. Taking advantage of new maps of marine intrusion under scenarios of 1 and 6 m sea-level rise, we calculated areal losses for all terrestrial ecoregions globally, with areal losses for particular ecoregions ranging from nil to complete. Marine intrusion is a global phenomenon, but its effects are most prominent in Southeast Asia and nearby islands, eastern North America, northeastern South America, and western Alaska. Making assumptions regarding faunal responses to reduced distributional areas of species endemic to ecoregions, we estimated likely numbers of extinctions caused by sea-level rise, and found that marine-intrusion-caused extinctions of narrow endemics are likely to be most prominent in northeastern South America, although anticipated extinctions in smaller numbers are scattered worldwide. This assessment serves as a complement to recent estimates of losses owing to changing climatic conditions, considering a dimension of biodiversity consequences of climate change that has not previously been taken into account. © 2010 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.","Biodiversity; Climate change; Ecoregions; Endemic species; Extinction; Marine intrusion; Sea-level change","biodiversity; climate change; ecoregion; endemic species; environmental disturbance; extinction risk; habitat fragmentation; sea level change; Alaska; North America; South America; Southeast Asia; United States",,,,,,"Anciães, M., Peterson, A.T., Climate change effects on neotropical manakin diversity based on ecological niche modeling (2006) Condor, 108, pp. 778-791; Araújo, M.B., Rahbek, C., How does climate change affect biodiversity? (2006) Science, 313, pp. 1396-1397; Araújo, M.B., Pearson, R.G., Thuiller, W., Erhard, M., Validation of species-climate impact models under climate change (2005) Glob Change Biol, 11, pp. 1504-1513; Bindschadler, R.A., Future of the West Antarctic ice sheet (1998) Science, 282, pp. 428-429; Bosello, F., Roson, R., Tol, R., Economy-wide estimates of the implications of climate change: Sea level rise (2007) Environ Res Econ, 37, pp. 549-571; Brooks, T.M., Pimm, S.L., Collar, N.J., The extent of deforestation predicts the number of birds threatened with extinction in insular South-east Asia (1997) Conserv Biol, 11, pp. 382-394; Brooks, T.M., Mittermeier, R.A., Mittermeier, C.G., da fonseca, G.A.B., Rylands, A.B., Konstant, W.R., Flick, P., Hilton-Taylor, C., Habitat loss and extinction in the hotspots of biodiversity (2002) Conserv Biol, 16, pp. 909-923; Buckley, L.B., Roughgarden, J., Biodiversity conservation: Effects of changes in climate and land use (2004) Nature, 430, p. 1; Carter, T.R., Jones, R.N., Lu, X., B